<?xml version="1.0"?>
<block>
  <name>GPredict Rotor</name>
  <key>gpredict_rotor</key>
  <category>[GPredict]</category>
  <import>import gpredict</import>
  <make>gpredict.rotor($minEl, "$gpredict_host()", $gpredict_port(), $verbose())</make>

  <param>
    <name>Min Elevation</name>
    <key>minEl</key>
    <value>20.0</value>
    <type>float</type>
  </param>
  
  <param>
    <name>Gpredict Host</name>
    <key>gpredict_host</key>
    <value>localhost</value>
    <type>string</type>
  </param>
  <param>
    <name>Gpredict Port</name>
    <key>gpredict_port</key>
    <value>4533</value>
    <type>int</type>
  </param>
  <param>
    <name>Verbose</name>
    <key>verbose</key>
    <value>True</value>
    <type>bool</type>
    <option>
      <name>Yes</name>
      <key>True</key>
    </option>
    <option>
      <name>No</name>
      <key>False</key>
    </option>
  </param>
  <source>
    <name>az_el</name>
    <type>message</type>
    <optional>1</optional>
  </source>
  <source>
    <name>state</name>
    <type>message</type>
    <optional>1</optional>
  </source>

 <doc>
This block is a rotctl-compatible block for receiving azimuth (az) and elevation (el) commands from external systems such as gpredict.  The system listens on a TCP connection for the appropriate command, and when received sets the specified flowgraph variable to the received value.  The azimuth and elevation are also output on a message block as metadata values (az and el) that can be used by other blocks.  
</doc>
</block>
